    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26b.48-50_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">48</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        225 Willard Way, Ithaca, <hi rend="caps">N.Y.</hi>
                        Sept. 17, 1958.
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear John: -</salute></opener> <p>I have thought of you so many times since that nice visit of the summer in your daughter's home. But only now am I getting around to writing. After my return, we <del>have been</del> <add>were</add> busy entertaining the children. <unclear>Trish</unclear>, our daughter, Alice Jean, and her husband, and the little granddaughter visited us. And then the <del/> other daughter, Kathleen, came, bringing her husband and the little grandson.. We had such an enjoyable time with the children. And indeed it is satisfying to note in the little ones the continuity of our lives. We shall pass <add>^on</add> some day, but we hope they will remain and for <unclear/> full times.</p>
                
                <p>This has been the most singular summer that I remember in Ithaca. The weather has been unusually cool and wet. I noted on Sept 12 in the 25 years ago <del/> items <add>^in the local paper</add> a <unclear>student</unclear> that the lowest temperatures reached on that day, 37 degrees, made a new record for <del>that</del><add>the</add> date in the weather history <unclear>of</unclear> its place. But on our Sept 12 on this very
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26b.48-50_0002"/>
                   
                <fw type="authorial">-2-</fw>
                <fw type="curatorial">49</fw>

                    year 35-+ was registered. The campus, while usually is brown at this time, is <add>as</add> green as in May. And last <del/> winter, with an aggregate snowfall of more than 90 inches, made another record, and of an different variety. Maybe someday the weather people will be able to explain.</p>
                
                <p>School is about to open here, and I suppose it has already opened at the <hi rend="caps">U.</hi> Of Mo. If so, that means that you are on television. How I wish I could see and hear you! But I trust that your performance is being recorded &#8212; I forget the word applicable here.</p>
                
                <p>The other night reading Jed Smith, I noted the references to the Canyon of the Green and to Henry's Fork. So I looked them up on the atlas, and knew just <unclear>when</unclear> the wonderful conversation took place, or rather where in your poetic imagination you arranged it.</p>
                
                <p>I am still trying, with <hi rend="caps">N.Y.</hi> agents and publishers, to get my book published, but as yet have nothing to report.</p>
                
                <p>Please remember me to your daughter and son-in-law. I did enjoy so much meeting them, and trust that the ailing leg is now well. I think of you so much and always with warmth and affection,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>Slade</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <opener><hi rend="caps">P.S.</hi></opener> <p>How did the <hi rend="caps">S.D.</hi> and Nebraska conferences come out?</p>
                </postscript>
                
            </div1>
            
            
